holarship, its language and technical content have so far resisted proper translation, a need whichthis book fills. The introduction provides not only the background to make Duarte's text comprehensible, but for the first time offers modern audiences a systematic point of access to the subject of medieval equestrianism in general. JEFFREY L. FORGENG is curator of Arms and Armor and Medieval Art at the Worcester Art Museum, and Adjunct Professor of History at Worcester Polytechnic Institute.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChivalryxEarly works to 1800. 0aHorsemanshipxEarly works to 1800. 0aHorsemanship. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArmor.  aArms.  aChivalry.  aDuarte of Portugal.  aEquestrianism.  aEuropean History.  aFencing.  aHorse.  aHorsemanship.  aMartial Arts.  aMedieval Culture.  aMedieval History.  aMedieval Society.  aMedieval Sports.  aMiddle Ages.  aMilitary History.  aSwordplay.  aWarfare.  aWeaponry.1 aForgeng, Jeffrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204628840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782046288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782046288/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles